A Quick Word on Specificity (Which Rule Wins?)
When multiple rules target the same element, CSS decides the winner using specificity — roughly, in order of increasing power:

• Element selectors (p) → weakest

• Class, attribute, and pseudo-class selectors (.card, [type="text"], :hover)

• ID selectors (#header) → strongest

• Inline styles (style="...") → stronger than any selector

• !important → overrides everything (use sparingly!)
css
p { color: black; } /* specificity: low */
.highlight { color: green; } /* specificity: medium — this wins if both apply */
#unique { color: red; } /* specificity: high — this wins over the class */If a <p class="highlight" id="unique"> element matches all three rules above, the text turns red — the ID selector has the highest specificity among these three.

Putting It All Together: A Mini Example
html
<div class="card">
<h3>Student Card</h3>
<p>Name: Aditi Sharma</p>
<p class="important">Status: Active</p>
<a href="profile.pdf">Download Profile</a>
</div>css
.card {
border: 1px solid #ddd;
padding: 16px;
border-radius: 8px;
}
.card h3 { /* descendant selector */
color: navy;
}
.card p.important { /* combined class selectors */
color: green;
font-weight: bold;
}
.card p + p { /* adjacent sibling selector */
margin-top: 8px;
}
.card a[href$=".pdf"]::after { /* attribute + pseudo-element */
content: " 📄";
}
.card a:hover { /* pseudo-class */
text-decoration: underline;
}Notice how combining selectors — element + class, attribute + pseudo-element — lets you target exactly the right piece of content with surgical precision, without cluttering your HTML with extra classes.

Final Thoughts
CSS selectors are the foundation of everything you’ll do in styling — from simple text color changes to building entire responsive layouts. The trick to mastering them isn’t memorizing every symbol at once; it’s practicing on a real page. Take any HTML page you’ve built, open your browser’s DevTools, and try selecting elements in different ways until it feels natural.
Once selectors click, concepts like the Box Model, Flexbox, and media queries (which you may have already explored) become much easier — because you’ll always know exactly which element you’re targeting before you style it.
Happy styling! 🎨

